"n.(牛马的)蹄 【英】 n. (牛马的)蹄(the entire foot of ungulate animals) 【记】 比较记忆：hood(帽兜 ), hook(挂钩), hoop(环，圈) n. (马, 牛或鹿等的)蹄; v 踢 【记】读: 胡夫－睡在金字塔里的哥们儿, 原来是暴君经常踢人. 【区】hood(n 帽兜); hook(n 钩; 吊钩) 【记】音：护肤，牛马的蹄子实际上是用来保护足底皮肤的 hoof (n.)  Old English hof ""hoof,"" from Proto-Germanic *hofaz (cognates: Old Saxon, Old Frisian hof, Old Norse hofr, Danish hov, Dutch hoef, German Huf ""hof""), from PIE *kop- ""to beat, strike"" (cognates: Sanskrit saphah ""hoof""). For spelling, see hood (n.1). hoof (v.)  ""to walk"" (hoof it), first attested 1640s, from hoof (n.); slang meaning ""to dance"" is 1920, American English (implied in hoofer). Related: Hoofed; hoofing."
